		<div id="comment_body_64118229"><p>According to car and driver</p><p><span class="substr"> </span> <i>Why hasn't ammonia received much attention in automotive contexts? For starters, it's not a great fuel. Ammonia is difficult to ignite at low temperatures, combusts over a narrow air-to-fuel ratio, and, among other things, can be prone to detonation. It boils at a chilly 28 degrees Fahrenheit and needs around 150 psi of pressure to remain liquid at the temperatures in which cars typically operate. Oh, and it's toxic.</i> </p><p> <a href="https://www.caranddriver.com/features/a45531791/ammonia-instead-of-gasoline-chinese-automaker-gac-suggests-it/" title="caranddriver.com">https://www.caranddriver.com/f...</a> [caranddriver.com] </p><p>Even if we solve all those issue</p></div>
