			<h4><a id="comment_link_64118519" name="comment_link_64118519" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23177285&amp;cid=64118519" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64118519)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64118519" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64118519); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~RossCWilliams">RossCWilliams</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~RossCWilliams">( 5513152 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64118519"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64118519">Where do you live that has a surplus of clean energy? There are places where hydro does that but even most of those grids still have peaker plants that supplement their hydro power. Most emission free sources of electricity have marginally cheap production costs. That means they are the first power used. So unless there is more than enough emission free power to provide for all the other uses, the power to charge your EV is not emission free.</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64118519">

